AB  - Under the compound effect of continuous global warming and rapid urbanization, China is experiencing extreme heat events with increased intensity, frequency, and duration, which pose a significant threat to human society. Nonetheless, research on the spatiotemporal patterns and regional characteristics of extreme heat disaster risk (EHDR) at the county level in China remains scarce. To address this gap, we have developed an analytical framework for extreme heat disaster systems and an evaluation system for EHDR indicators. This framework measures the extent of EHDR and examines the dominant subsystems and their transformation processes across different regions. The results show that: (1) The spatial clustering types of EHDR in China's counties are mainly "High-High" and "Low-Low", forming a significant northeast-southwest low-value belt and a northwest-southeast high-value center; (2) In China, 91.49% of counties exhibited an increasing trend in EHDR from 2000 to 2018, while the counties experiencing reduced disaster risk are predominantly located in northern China; (3) The average values of EHDR and its subsystems are significantly higher in the Northwest and the Middle and Lower reaches of the Yangtze River compared to other regions, establishing these areas as high-value clusters; (4) The transformation of dominant subsystems across regions reveals significant geographic differences. In Western China, the environment predominates; in the northern regions, environment-exposure is dominant; and in the southern regions, the hazard is the primary factor. Notably, the causes of disaster risk in the Middle reaches of the Yellow River and the Lower reaches of the Yangtze River are more complex. These findings enhance the understanding of EHDR dynamics within the framework of rapid urbanization and climate change.
