AB  - Oases in arid regions critically regulate surface and air temperatures by altering surface energy partitioning, yet the biophysical mechanisms controlling their thermal regulation efficiency and the trade-off between cooling benefits and water consumption remain poorly quantified. To bridge this knowledge gap, we developed the Oasis Cooling Efficiency (OCE) index − a biophysical metric synergistically combining satellite-derived land surface temperature with Priestley-Taylor (PT) model-based evapotranspiration (ET) estimates. Using partial derivative analysis, we quantified the sensitivity of OCE and Oasis Cooling Intensity (OCI) to key environmental drivers. Our results demonstrated that: 1) OCI exhibited strong diurnal asymmetry, with daytime cooling averaging 5.01 K but diminishing nocturnally (−0.82 K). OCI was driven by ET contrasts (ΔET, r = 0.79) and albedo differences (ΔAbd, r = 0.38), with ΔET contributing dominantly (elasticity = 0.48). Specifically, VPD dominated OCI variation (−39.86%), while soil moisture (SM) and NDVI enhanced it (+17.68%, +19.68%). 2) OCE demonstrated significant heterogeneity (0.06–0.32 K/mm), peaking in forests (1.25 K/mm) and showing hyperbolic decay with ΔET. VPD dominated OCE declines (−16%), while SM enhanced it (+1.4%). 3) OCI increased with the intensification of both atmospheric and soil droughts, with atmospheric drought exerting a stronger influence. OCE decreased under atmospheric drought but increased under soil drought. Compound droughts amplified OCI (+65%) while collapsing OCE (−62%), exposing unsustainable water costs. These findings establish a framework for optimizing oasis cooling benefits while balancing water conservation in arid regions.
